"></span><section data-level=3D"1" id=3D"ref1"><!--[PREMOD1]--><span class=
=3D"marker PREMOD1 mod-inline"></span><p class=3D"topic-paragraph"><strong>=
<span id=3D"ref89962"></span>Diophantine equation</strong>,  <a href=3D"htt=
ps://www.britannica.com/science/equation" class=3D"md-crosslink autoxref " =
data-show-preview=3D"true">equation</a> involving only sums, products, and =
powers in which all the constants are integers and the only solutions of in=
terest are integers. For example, 3<em>x</em>&nbsp;+&nbsp;7<em>y</em>&nbsp;=
=3D&nbsp;1 or <em>x</em><sup>2</sup>&nbsp;=E2=88=92&nbsp;<em>y</em><sup>2</=
sup>&nbsp;=3D&nbsp;<em>z</em><sup>3</sup>, where <em>x</em>, <em>y</em>, an=
d <em>z</em> are integers. Named in honour of the 3rd-century Greek mathema=
tician <a href=3D"https://www.britannica.com/biography/Diophantus" class=3D=
"md-crosslink " data-show-preview=3D"true">Diophantus of Alexandria</a>, th=
ese equations were first systematically solved by Hindu mathematicians begi=
nning with <a href=3D"https://www.britannica.com/biography/Aryabhata-I" cla=
ss=3D"md-crosslink " data-show-preview=3D"true">Aryabhata</a> (c. 476=E2=80=
=93550).</p><div id=3D"AdThrive_Content_1_tablet" class=3D"adthrive-ad adth=
rive-content adthrive-content-1 adthrive-ad-cls" style=3D"min-height: 250px=
;"></div><!--[MOD1]--><span class=3D"marker MOD1 mod-inline"></span><!--[PR=
EMOD2]--><span class=3D"marker PREMOD2 mod-inline"></span><p class=3D"topic=
-paragraph">Diophantine equations fall into three classes: those with no so=
lutions, those with only finitely many solutions, and those with infinitely=
 many solutions. For example, the equation 6<em>x</em>&nbsp;=E2=88=92&nbsp;=
9<em>y</em>&nbsp;=3D&nbsp;29 has no solutions, but the equation 6<em>x</em>=
 =E2=88=92 9<em>y</em> =3D 30, which upon division by 3 reduces to 2<em>x</=
em>&nbsp;=E2=88=92&nbsp;3<em>y</em>&nbsp;=3D&nbsp;10, has infinitely many. =
For example, <em>x</em>&nbsp;=3D&nbsp;20, <em>y</em>&nbsp;=3D&nbsp;10 is a =
solution, and so is <em>x</em>&nbsp;=3D&nbsp;20&nbsp;+&nbsp;3<em>t</em>, <e=
m>y</em>&nbsp;=3D&nbsp;10&nbsp;+&nbsp;2<em>t</em> for every <a href=3D"http=
s://www.britannica.com/science/integer" class=3D"md-crosslink autoxref " da=
ta-show-preview=3D"true">integer</a> <em>t</em>, positive, negative, or zer=
o. This is called a one-parameter family of solutions, with <em>t</em> bein=
g the arbitrary <a class=3D"md-dictionary-link md-dictionary-tt-off mw" dat=
a-term=3D"parameter" href=3D"https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/par=
ameter" data-type=3D"MW">parameter</a>.</p><div class=3D"js-qf-module qf-mo=
dule px-40 px-sm-20 py-15 mx-auto module-spacing font-14 bg-gray-50 rounded=
">

