Congruence methods</a> provide a useful tool in determining the number of s=
olutions to a Diophantine equation. Applied to the simplest Diophantine equ=
ation, <em>a</em><em>x</em> + <em>b</em><em>y</em> =3D <em>c</em>, where <e=
m>a</em>, <em>b</em>, and <em>c</em> are nonzero integers, these methods sh=
ow that the equation has either no solutions or infinitely many, according =
to whether the greatest common divisor (GCD) of <em>a</em> and <em>b</em> d=
ivides <em>c</em>: if not, there are no solutions; if it does, there are in=
finitely many solutions, and they form a one-parameter family of solutions.=
