div class=3D"md-sentinel--spy-target"></div><section data-level=3D"1" id=3D=
"ref1" data-has-spy=3D"true"><!--[PREMOD1]--><span class=3D"marker PREMOD1 =
mod-inline"></span><p class=3D"topic-paragraph"><strong><span id=3D"ref5086=
77"></span>number theory</strong>,  branch of <a href=3D"https://www.britan=
nica.com/science/mathematics" class=3D"md-crosslink " data-show-preview=3D"=
true">mathematics</a> concerned with properties of the positive <span id=3D=
"ref508678"></span><a href=3D"https://www.britannica.com/science/integer" c=
lass=3D"md-crosslink " data-show-preview=3D"true">integers</a> (1, 2, 3, =
=E2=80=A6). Sometimes called =E2=80=9Chigher arithmetic,=E2=80=9D it is amo=
ng the oldest and most natural of mathematical pursuits.</p><!--[MOD1]--><s=
pan class=3D"marker MOD1 mod-inline"></span><!--[PREMOD2]--><span class=3D"=
marker PREMOD2 mod-inline"></span><p class=3D"topic-paragraph">Number theor=
y has always fascinated <a class=3D"md-dictionary-link md-dictionary-tt-off=
 eb" data-term=3D"amateurs" href=3D"https://www.britannica.com/dictionary/a=
mateurs" data-type=3D"EB">amateurs</a> as well as professional mathematicia=
ns. In contrast to other branches of mathematics, many of the problems and =
theorems of number theory can be understood by laypersons, although solutio=
ns to the problems and proofs of the theorems often require a sophisticated=
 mathematical background.</p><!--[MOD2]--><span class=3D"marker MOD2 mod-in=
line"></span><!--[PREMOD3]--><span class=3D"marker PREMOD3 mod-inline"></sp=
an><p class=3D"topic-paragraph">Until the mid-20th century, number theory w=
as considered the purest branch of mathematics, with no direct applications=
 to the real world. The advent of digital <span id=3D"ref796034"></span><a =
href=3D"https://www.britannica.com/technology/computer" class=3D"md-crossli=
nk " data-show-preview=3D"true">computers</a> and digital communications re=
vealed that number theory could provide unexpected answers to real-world pr=
oblems. At the same time, improvements in computer technology enabled numbe=
r theorists to make remarkable advances in factoring large numbers, determi=
ning <a href=3D"https://www.britannica.com/science/prime-number-theorem" cl=
ass=3D"md-crosslink " data-show-preview=3D"true">primes</a>, testing conjec=
tures, and solving numerical problems once considered out of reach.</p><!--=
[MOD3]--><span class=3D"marker MOD3 mod-inline"></span><!--[PREMOD4]--><spa=
n class=3D"marker PREMOD4 mod-inline"></span><p class=3D"topic-paragraph">M=
odern number theory is a broad subject that is classified into subheadings =
such as elementary number theory, <a href=3D"https://www.britannica.com/sci=
ence/algebraic-number" class=3D"md-crosslink autoxref " data-show-preview=
=3D"true">algebraic number</a> theory, <a class=3D"md-dictionary-link md-di=
ctionary-tt-off mw" data-term=3D"analytic" href=3D"https://www.merriam-webs=
ter.com/dictionary/analytic" data-type=3D"MW">analytic</a> number theory, g=
eometric number theory, and probabilistic number theory. These categories r=
eflect the methods used to address problems concerning the integers.</p><!-=
-[MOD4]--><span class=3D"marker MOD4 mod-inline"></span></section>         =
<!--[H2]--><span class=3D"marker h2"></span><div class=3D"md-sentinel--spy-=
target"></div><section data-level=3D"1" id=3D"ref233895" data-has-spy=3D"tr=
ue"> <h2 class=3D"h1">From prehistory through Classical Greece</h2> <!--[PR=
EMOD5]--><span class=3D"marker PREMOD5 mod-inline"></span><p class=3D"topic=
-paragraph">The ability to count dates back to prehistoric times. This is e=
vident from archaeological <a class=3D"md-dictionary-link md-dictionary-tt-=
off mw" data-term=3D"artifacts" href=3D"https://www.merriam-webster.com/dic=
tionary/artifacts" data-type=3D"MW">artifacts</a>, such as a 10,000-year-ol=
d bone from the Congo region of Africa with tally marks scratched upon it=
=E2=80=94signs of an unknown ancestor counting something. Very near the daw=
n of civilization, people had grasped the idea of =E2=80=9Cmultiplicity=E2=
=80=9D and thereby had taken the first steps toward a study of numbers.</p>=
<a class=3D"link-module shadow-sm d-block qa-quiz-module" href=3D"https://w=
ww.britannica.com/quiz/Numbers-and-mathematics">
