6]--><span class=3D"marker PREMOD6 mod-inline"></span><p class=3D"topic-par=
agraph">It is certain that an understanding of numbers existed in ancient M=
esopotamia, <a href=3D"https://www.britannica.com/place/Egypt" class=3D"md-=
crosslink autoxref " data-show-preview=3D"true">Egypt</a>, China, and India=
, for tablets, papyri, and temple carvings from these early <a class=3D"md-=
dictionary-link md-dictionary-tt-off mw" data-term=3D"cultures" href=3D"htt=
ps://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/cultures" data-type=3D"MW">cultures=
</a> have survived. A <span id=3D"ref796455"></span><a href=3D"https://www.=
britannica.com/place/Babylon-ancient-city-Mesopotamia-Asia" class=3D"md-cro=
sslink " data-show-preview=3D"true">Babylonian</a> tablet known as <span id=
=3D"ref796456"></span>Plimpton 322 (c. 1700 <span class=3D"text-smallcaps">=
bce</span>) is a case in point. In modern notation, it displays number trip=
les <em>x</em>, <em>y</em>, and <em>z</em> with the property that <em>x</em=
><sup>2</sup> + <em>y</em><sup>2</sup> =3D <em>z</em><sup>2</sup>. One such=
 triple is 2,291, 2,700, and 3,541, where 2,291<sup>2</sup> + 2,700<sup>2</=
sup> =3D 3,541<sup>2</sup>. This certainly reveals a degree of number theor=
etic sophistication in ancient Babylon.</p><!--[MOD6]--><span class=3D"mark=
er MOD6 mod-inline"></span> <!--[PREMOD7]--><span class=3D"marker PREMOD7 m=
od-inline"></span><p class=3D"topic-paragraph">Despite such isolated result=
s, a general theory of numbers was nonexistent. For this=E2=80=94as with so=
 much of theoretical mathematics=E2=80=94one must look to the Classical <sp=
an id=3D"ref796457"></span><a href=3D"https://www.britannica.com/place/anci=
ent-Greece" class=3D"md-crosslink " data-show-preview=3D"true">Greeks</a>, =
whose groundbreaking achievements displayed an odd fusion of the mystical t=
endencies of the <span id=3D"ref508698"></span><a href=3D"https://www.brita=
nnica.com/science/Pythagoreanism" class=3D"md-crosslink " data-show-preview=
=3D"true">Pythagoreans</a> and the severe logic of <a href=3D"https://www.b=
ritannica.com/biography/Euclid-Greek-mathematician" class=3D"md-crosslink "=
 data-show-preview=3D"true">Euclid</a>=E2=80=99s <em>Elements</em> (c. 300 =
<span class=3D"text-smallcaps">bce</span>).</p><div class=3D"module-spacing=
