-><span class=3D"marker PREMOD8 mod-inline"></span><p class=3D"topic-paragr=
aph">According to tradition, <a href=3D"https://www.britannica.com/biograph=
y/Pythagoras" class=3D"md-crosslink " data-show-preview=3D"true">Pythagoras=
</a> (c. 580=E2=80=93500 <span class=3D"text-smallcaps">bce</span>) worked =
in southern Italy amid devoted followers. His philosophy enshrined number a=
s the unifying <a class=3D"md-dictionary-link md-dictionary-tt-off eb" data=
-term=3D"concept" href=3D"https://www.britannica.com/dictionary/concept" da=
ta-type=3D"EB">concept</a> necessary for understanding everything from plan=
etary motion to musical harmony. Given this viewpoint, it is not surprising=
 that the Pythagoreans attributed quasi-rational properties to certain numb=
ers.</p><!--[MOD8]--><span class=3D"marker MOD8 mod-inline"></span> <!--[PR=
EMOD9]--><span class=3D"marker PREMOD9 mod-inline"></span><p class=3D"topic=
-paragraph">For instance, they attached significance to <span id=3D"ref5086=
96"></span><a href=3D"https://www.britannica.com/science/perfect-number" cl=
ass=3D"md-crosslink " data-show-preview=3D"true">perfect numbers</a>=E2=80=
=94i.e., those that equal the sum of their proper divisors. Examples are 6 =
(whose proper divisors 1, 2, and 3 sum to 6) and 28 (1 + 2 + 4 + 7 + 14). T=
he Greek philosopher <span id=3D"ref796459"></span><a href=3D"https://www.b=
ritannica.com/biography/Nicomachus-of-Gerasa" class=3D"md-crosslink " data-=
show-preview=3D"true">Nicomachus of Gerasa</a> (flourished c. 100 <span cla=
ss=3D"text-smallcaps">ce</span>), writing centuries after Pythagoras but cl=
early in his philosophical debt, stated that perfect numbers represented =
=E2=80=9Cvirtues, wealth, moderation, propriety, and beauty.=E2=80=9D (Some=
 modern writers label such nonsense numerical theology.)</p><div class=3D"j=
s-qf-module qf-module px-40 px-sm-20 py-15 mx-auto module-spacing font-14 b=
